        "subject": "LU-20039 lnet: preserve router buffer sizing on re-enable",
        "message": "LU-20039 lnet: preserve router buffer sizing on re-enable\n\nWhen sanity-lnet test 257 disables routing and then enables it\nagain, the router can try to allocate the default large buffer\npool instead of the small buffer counts configured at module\nload time. On small-memory test nodes this can trigger an\nallocation failure like:\n\nlnet: error allocating 1024x16 page router buffers on CPT 0: rc = -12\n\nThe disable and re-enable path was losing the configured router\nbuffer sizes. lnet_rtrpools_disable() reset tiny_router_buffers,\nsmall_router_buffers, and large_router_buffers to zero, and\nlnet_rtrpools_enable() rebuilt existing pools by calling\nlnet_rtrpools_adjust_helper() with 0, 0, 0. In this interface, zero\nmeans to fall back to the default sizing, not to preserve the current\nvalues.\n\nFix this by keeping the configured buffer counts across routing\ndisable, and by having lnet_rtrpools_enable() rebuild the\nexisting pools with the saved tiny, small, and large router\nbuffer values. This makes routing re-enable follow the same\neffective sizing as the initial router pool allocation.\n\nTest-Parameters: trivial\nFixes: ed70ccb471 (\"LU-15135 lnet: Graceful router removal and addition\")\nSigned-off-by: Chris Horn <chris.horn@hpe.com>\nChange-Id: I6edff22744275bfe2fc95496d8a31d802803cb76\nReviewed-on: https://review.whamcloud.com/c/fs/lustre-release/+/65153\nReviewed-by: Oleg Drokin <green@whamcloud.com>\nReviewed-by: Cyril Bordage <cbordage@whamcloud.com>\nTested-by: Maloo <maloo@whamcloud.com>\nReviewed-by: Andreas Dilger <adilger@thelustrecollective.com>\nTested-by: jenkins <devops@whamcloud.com>\n"
      },
      "branch": "refs/heads/master"
    }
  },
